WHY INGRESS EXISTS?

>> Imagine you have 5 services:
/api --> backend
/auth --> auth service
/ --> frontend

>> Without Ingress
you will need : 
5 LoadBalancers 
5 public IPs 
Expensive + messy 

>> with Ingress

User → ONE LoadBalancer → Ingress → Multiple Services
Single entry point for all apps

>> Ingress is a Kubernetes API object that defines rules for routing external HTTP/HTTPS traffic to internal services.

>> Ingress does NOT handle traffic itself
>> It only defines rules

>> Make your HTTP (or HTTPS) network service available using a protocol-aware configuration mechanism, that understands web concepts like URIs, hostnames, paths, and more. The Ingress concept lets you map traffic to different backends based on rules you define via the Kubernetes API.

>> Ingress exposes HTTP and HTTPS routes from outside the cluster to services within the cluster. Traffic routing is controlled by rules defines on the Ingress resources.

![alt text](ingress.svg)

>> You must have an Ingress controller to satisfy an Ingress

INGRESS CONTROLLER

>> Ingress Controller is the actual component that reads Ingress rules and routes traffic accordingly.

Ingress = rule book 
Ingress Controller = traffic police 

>> Popular Ingress Controllers
NGINX Ingress Controller
Traefik
HAProxy

HOW INGRESS WORKS?

User → LoadBalancer → Ingress Controller → Service → Pod

User hits domain (example.com)
LoadBalancer forwards request
Ingress Controller reads rules set by the Ingress
Routes to correct Service
Service sends to Pod

YAML FILE

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: my-ingress
spec:
  rules:
   - host: example.com
     http:
       paths:
       - path: /api
         pathType: Prefix
         backend:
           service:
             name: api-service
             port: 
              number: 80
      - path: /
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: frontend-service
            port:
              number: 80

Requests:
example.com/api → api-service
example.com/ → frontend-service

TYPES OF ROUTING based on HTTP request details:

1. Path Based Routing
> Routing based on URL path
example.com/api → backend
example.com/ → frontend

When a request comes, 
Ingress Controller checks:
Path = /api
Matches rule → routes to backend service

2. Host Based Routing
> Routing based on domain name
api.example.com → backend
app.example.com → frontend

TLS/HTTPS
Transport Layer Security
spec:
  tls:
  - hosts:
    - example.com
    secretName: tls-secret

>TLS secret contains:
SSL certificate
Private key

> Real Benefit
Secure communication
HTTPS termination at Ingress

> Why TLS is Needed

Without TLS:
HTTP → plain text → insecure 

With TLS:
HTTPS → encrypted → secure 

> TLS Flow
User (HTTPS)
   ↓
Ingress Controller (decrypts TLS)
   ↓
Service (HTTP)
   ↓
Pod

> TLS ends at Ingress, not at the Pod

>What is tls-secret?
A Kubernetes Secret containing:
Certificate (tls.crt)
Private key (tls.key)

>> Why Ingress is Powerful?

1. Single Entry Point

Without Ingress :
5 services → 5 LoadBalancers → 5 IPs 
With Ingress :
1 LoadBalancer → routes everything 

2. Cost Efficient
Cloud LoadBalancers cost money
Without Ingress → expensive
With Ingress → one LB only

3. Centralized Routing
All routing defined in one place
Benefits: Easier debugging and updates

4. SSL Termination
No need to manage SSL in each service


INGRESS VS LOADBALANCER

Feature	LoadBalancer	Ingress
Level	L4 (TCP)	L7 (HTTP/HTTPS)
Routing	Basic	Advanced
Cost	High	Low
Entry Points	Multiple	Single

Ingress works at Layer 7 (Application Layer)
LoadBalancer works at Layer 4 (Transport Layer)

SCENARIOS

1. Ingress not working
>> causes: No Ingress Controller installed and wrong rules
>> Debug:
kubectl get pods -n ingress-nginx
kubectl describe ingress <name>

2. 404 Not Found
>> Means Rules not matching
>> Fix : Check path/host config

3. Service Not Reachable
>> Cause : Backend service wrong
> port mismatch

4. TLS not working
> causes : wrong secret
> certicate missing

5. DNS not resolving
> cause: Domain not mapped to LB IP

CMDS

kubectl get ingress
kubectl describe ingress <name>
kubectl get svc
kubectl get pods -n ingress-nginx


